The primary method for terminating a C program is through the use of the `exit()` function. This function gracefully terminates the program and returns a status code to the operating system.

```c
#include <stdio.h>
#include <stdlib.h>

int main() {
  printf("Program terminating...\n");
  exit(0); // Exit with a status code of 0 (indicating success)
  // The following line will not be executed
  printf("This will not be printed.\n");
  return 0;
}
```

Alternatively, you can use the `return` statement within the `main()` function. This also terminates the program and returns a status code to the operating system. A return value of 0 typically indicates successful execution.

```c
#include <stdio.h>

int main() {
  printf("Program terminating...\n");
  return 0;
}
```

However, it’s crucial to understand that abruptly terminating a program – using methods such as Ctrl+C – can lead to data corruption and unpredictable behavior. The `exit()` function provides a more controlled and reliable method of termination.

(I shift slightly, a touch of weariness in my voice.)

Furthermore, be mindful of resource cleanup. Before terminating a program, it’s essential to release any allocated memory – close any open files – and perform any necessary cleanup operations. Failure to do so can lead to resource leaks and instability.

